<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-554-171  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 554 171.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Oct 29 1990 v7 n44 p21(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hospital improves services through electronic imaging. (on-linemedical records)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Molloy, Maureen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Burbank Hospital in Fitchburg, MA, is implementing an imagingsystem that allows hospital personnel to directly obtain patientfiles on-line.andP;  Electronic imaging allows simultaneous access topatient files and decreases expenses of handling and storage ofmedical records.andP;  Under the new system, patient medical recordsare captured electronically as images using a document scanner.andO;During this process the images are indexed by patient name andnumber, physician and principal diagnosis.andP;  The records are thenstored on optical disks.andP;  Hospital staff can make data baseinquiries and are able to access images on microcomputerworkstations throughout the hospital.andP;  Optical disk imaging givesdoctors more information in less time.andP;  In some cases, fast accesscan help save lives when a physician must act quickly andinformation is needed immediately.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Hospital Information SystemsOn-LineMedical RecordsImaging TechnologyAccess Methods.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>